==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lover
<hw>Lov"er</hw> <pr>(l⟦ucr⟧v"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who loves; one who is in love; -- usually limited, in the
singular, to a person of the male sex.</def>
<rj><au>Gower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love is blind, and <qex>lovers</qex> can not see⟦br⟧
The pretty follies that themselves commit.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A friend; one strongly attached to another; one who
greatly desires the welfare of any person or thing; <as>as, a
<ex>lover</ex> of his country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I slew my best <qex>lover</qex> for the good of Rome.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who has a strong liking for anything, as books,
science, or music.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>lover</xex> of knowledge.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>T. Burnet.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One who is involved in a sexual relationship with
another; <as>as, she took a <ex>lover</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 872 --></p>

